  <section class="section-pad" style="background:var(--white);">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Signs Your Liverpool Heating System Needs Replacing</h2>
      <p class="section-sub">Liverpool's older housing stock means many properties are running on heating systems installed 20 or more years ago. Here are the signs it is time to upgrade.</p>

      <div class="sign-item">
        <span class="sign-icon">!</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Radiators cold at the top or bottom</strong>
          <p>Cold spots on radiators indicate sludge and scale build-up blocking the water flow. A power flush can often resolve this without a full replacement.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sign-item">
        <span class="sign-icon">!</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Some rooms not heating at all</strong>
          <p>Rooms that have never been connected to the central heating system, or where radiators have been removed, can be added to your existing system from £200 per radiator.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sign-item">
        <span class="sign-icon">!</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Old gravity-fed system with tanks in the loft</strong>
          <p>Many Liverpool Victorian properties have old gravity-fed open-vented systems with header tanks in the loft and hot water cylinders. Converting to a modern sealed system dramatically improves efficiency and reliability.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sign-item">
        <span class="sign-icon">!</span>
        <div>
          <strong>System making noise or losing pressure regularly</strong>
          <p>A noisy, inefficient system that regularly loses pressure indicates either a power flush is overdue or components need replacing. Both are far more cost-effective to address early.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sign-item">
        <span class="sign-icon">!</span>
        <div>
          <strong>High energy bills despite a reasonably new boiler</strong>
          <p>If your boiler is relatively new but your heating bills remain high, the issue is often the distribution system: undersized radiators, no thermostatic radiator valves or poor system design.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sign-item">
        <span class="sign-icon">!</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Property has no central heating at all</strong>
          <p>A significant number of Liverpool's older properties including bedsits, converted flats and some terraced houses have never had central heating. A full installation starts from £3,500.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

